After the previous change of the contentmanager's references, the destructor is finally called. The issue is that the unload of assets still does not happen, resulting in huge memory leaks if the unload is not called manually.

When I call Unload() manually, it disposes 22 textures in my case, resulting in no memory leak.
When I don't call it manually, but added Unload() to the destructor, it seems to dispose all 22 textures too, but the memory usage does not actually decrease.

Code to reproduce:

``` C#
for (int i = 0; i<10; i++)
{
    ContentManager cm = new ContentManager(this.Services);
    cm.Load<Texture2D> = "Content/whatever";
}
```

